  "title": "Proof by Cases",
  "body": " Proof by Cases  Idea: ``Proof by Cases\" is a type of direct proof. We use proof by cases when we might not have enough hypotheses (like the whole hypothesis is `` is an integer\"), or if the conclusion suggests cases (like ``...is even\" or ``...is a type 1 integer\"). Proof by Cases works when you break down the problem and do ``sub proofs\" that will `` cover\" the whole hypothesis. E.g.., if the hypothesis is `` is an integer\" then you could do 2 sub proofs - one where is an even integer and one where is an odd integer. Since all integers are either even or odd, you've proven the result for all integers!    For all integers , is even.    Pre-proof analysis:  "
